<h4>
  Where is the CED now?
</h4>

<p>
  “As the community has evolved, CED is happy to have played a role in the ecosystem. Traditionally focused on seed stage companies and connecting them with their first dollars, geting them ready for their pitch, things have changed to help support the ever-changing landscape.”
</p>

<p>
  In the past 18 months, CED has begun to focus its efforts on 3 main themes. Mentoring &amp; education, investor relations, and public relations. Here are some of the ways they work with companies.
</p>

<h5 class="margin-top">
  Mentoring and education for entrepreneurs
</h5>

<ul>
  <li>Focusing on working with slightly more mature companies who have product, traction, and revenue.</li>
  <li>CED has a mentoring program with MIT to give startups access to senior operators who can give perspective that are unbiased.</li>
  <li>Work with entrepreneurs to make sure their fundraising strategy and pitch is in place.</li>
</ul>

<h5>Investor relations</h5>

<ul>
  <li>CED is tracking over 1500 Triangle/NC companies in a database with key partnerships, revenue, key hires and other metrics to determine success. They have relationships with 300+ investor groups and connect those companies with investors.</li>
</ul>

<h5>Public relations</h5>

<ul>
  <li>
    The CED focuses on sharing the story of the companies they work with. These companies’ customers, partners, investors, and acquirers are external to North Carolina and the more the CED is able to strategically place stories of these companies to get them visibility, the better for the overall North Carolina startup ecosystem.</li>
</ul>

